"Wollaton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Touchet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Anastasie, Denys, Evest, Minos, Rodolph, Vernice.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a small grove, from a diminutive of Old French <i>toche</i> ‘grove’.","History: René Touchet from Thorigné-d'Anjou in Maine-et-Loire, France, married Marie Caillé in Saint-Laurent, Île-de-Montreal, QC, in 1746."],"variants":[{"name":"Touchette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Marcel, Pierre, Armand, Collette, Euclide, Henri, Hilaire, Huguette.","Altered form of French   Touchet  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Touchet was born about 1208. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Matilda Burnell."},"et":{"about 1208–":"umbes 1208–Surnud","1218–Female":"1218–Surnud","1231–1312":"1231–1312","1266–1332":"1266–1332","1208–Male":"1208–Surnud","about 1208":"umbes 1208","1312":"1312","ABT. 1231":"umbes 1231","1266":"1266","1332":"1332","1231":"1231","1208":"1208","1218":"1218","of Haynton, Lin